{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}} {{Use British English|date=July 2015}} {{Infobox person | name = Finlay Macintyre | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birthname = | birth_date = 1889 | birth_place = [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]], Scotland | death_date = 20 June 1940 (age 50 or 51) | death_place = [[Inner Seas off the West Coast of Scotland]] | occupation = [[Sea captain]] | nationality = [[Scottish people|Scottish]] | footnotes = }} [[File:Certificate of Competency for Finlay Black Macintyre.jpg|thumb|Certificate of Competency for Finlay Black Macintyre]]
'''Finlay Black Macintyre''' (1889 – 20 June 1940) was a [[sea captain]] in the [[Merchant navy]]
Macintyre gained his certificate of competency as master of a foreign-going steamship on 17 June 1925. Fourteen years later, he was captain of the [[SS Empire Conveyor|SS ''Empire Conveyor'']] cargo ship during [[World War II]] when, on 20 June 1940, it was torpedoed by German [[submarine]] {{GS|U-122|1939|2}} in the [[Inner Seas off the West Coast of Scotland]], {{convert|50|nmi|km}} south west of [[Barra Head]], Scotland, at {{coord|56|16|N|8|10|W}}. The ship sank before the rescue ships reached her. The crew took to [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboats and liferafts]] but one of them was swamped at launch, killing Macintyre,<ref>UK and Ireland, Masters and Mates, Certificates, 1850-1927, Certificate #0012007 for Finlay Black McIntyre as Master of a foreign-going steamship</ref> the second engineer and the cook.
==Personal life== Macintyre was born in 1889 in [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]], to William (1851 – 1900) and Mary Macintyre ([[née]] Black) (1856 – 1926). He was one of the couple's six children.
He married Hilda Morrison, with whom he had one child, a son Eric William Macintyre born on 3 May 1923. Still going strong.
